definition.value: A compound RC(=O)H, in which a carbonyl group is bonded to one hydrogen atom and to one R group.
A C4-dicarboxylate resulting from the removal of a proton from both carboxylic acid groups of enol-oxaloacetic acid.
An organic disulfide obtained by oxidative dimerisation of homocysteine.
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid where the methyl group has been hydroxylated.
A glycerophosphoglycerol that is glycerol in which the hydrogen of one of the primary hydroxy groups has been replaced by a phosphatidyl group.
A methyl-L-alanine in which one of the the amino hydrogen of L-alanine is replaced by a methyl group.
A carbohydrate that is an acyclic polyol having the general formula HOCH2[CH(OH)]nCH2OH (formally derivable from an aldose by reduction of the carbonyl group).
An N-acyl-L-amino acid that is L-glutamic acid in which one of the amine hydrogens is substituted by an acetyl group.
The six-membered ring form of L-arabinose.
A beta-D-galactopyranoside having a methyl substituent at the anomeric position.
The carbon oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from carbonic acid.

A linear copolymer macromolecule composed of homopolymeric blocks of 1->4-linked beta-D-mannuronic acid and alpha-L-guluronic acid residues, covalently linked together in different sequences or blocks.
An optically active form of cysteine having L-configuration.
A pyrimidine nucleoside in which cytosine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(1)-glycosidic bond.
A phthalate that is the dianion obtained by the deprotonation of both the carboxy groups of phthalic acid.

A common and naturally occurring pyrimidine nucleobase in which the pyrimidine ring is substituted with two oxo groups at positions 2 and 4. Found in RNA, it base pairs with adenine and replaces thymine during DNA transcription.
The simplest member of the class toluenes consisting of a benzene core which bears a single methyl substituent.
A cyclic carotene obtained by dimerisation of all-trans-retinol. A strongly-coloured red-orange pigment abundant in plants and fruit and the most active and important provitamin A carotenoid.
Homocysteine with L configuration.
A straight chain alkane composed of 8 carbon atoms.

A glucooligosaccharide derived from glucose monomers linked via alpha-D-1,4 bonds as in maltose.  The term is commonly applied to the series of linear oligosaccharides composed of two, three, four, five and six such units of glucose.
A purine nucleoside in which hypoxanthine is attached to ribofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond.
A  hydroxybenzaldehyde that is benzaldehyde substituted with a hydroxy group at position C-4.
An aldehydic acid which consists of benzoic acid substituted by a formyl group at position 2. Metabolite of ampicillin phthalidyl ester.
Any D-aldose having a chain of six carbon atoms in the molecule.
A a deoxyketohexose comprising L-tagatose with the hydroxy group at position 6 replaced by hydrogen.
A ferulic acid consisting of trans-cinnamic acid bearing methoxy and hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively on the phenyl ring.
A flavin mononucleotide that is riboflavin (vitamin B2) in which the primary hydroxy group has been converted to its dihydrogen phosphate ester.
A nitrogen oxoanion formed by loss of a proton from nitric acid. Principal species present at pH 7.3.
A glucose with D-configuration.
Any sphingomyelin having sphingosine as the sphingoid component.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is salicylic acid in which the hydrogen ortho to the carboxylic acid group is substituted by a methyl group.
A indol-3-yl carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(indol-3-yl)pyruvic acid
A macrolide antibiotic that is tylonolide having mono- and diglycosyl moieties attached to two of its hydroxy groups. It is found naturally as a fermentation product of Streptomyces fradiae.
A D-glucopyranose 6-phosphate where alpha-D-glucose is the sugar component.
A phosphosphingolipid consisting of sphingosine having a phosphocholine moiety attached to its primary hydroxyl group.
An organochlorine compound that is dichloro-substituted acetamide containing a nitrobenzene ring, an amide bond and two alcohol functions.
